aws::graph::propositions: # Aviation Accident Report for Robinson Helicopter Company R44 II in Pahrump, Nevada
The accident occurred in Pahrump, Nevada.
The accident occurred on August 24, 2014, at 06:50 Local time.
The aircraft involved was a Robinson Helicopter Company R44 II.
The defining event of the accident was a total loss of engine power.
The flight was conducted under Part 91: General aviation - Personal.
The accident number was WPR14LA353.
The aircraft registration was N4246Z.
The aircraft sustained substantial damage.
The accident resulted in 1 minor injury.
The commercial pilot was practicing an autorotation when the incident occurred.
The total loss of engine power occurred at approximately 3,500 feet above ground level.
The pilot made several unsuccessful attempts to restart the engine.
The pilot performed an autorotation emergency landing.
During the landing, the helicopter slid forward about 20 feet.
The helicopter's skids dug into the dry lakebed.
The helicopter nosed over after the skids dug into the dry lakebed.
The main rotor blades impacted the ground after the helicopter nosed over.
The helicopter came to rest on its side.
A postaccident examination of the airframe revealed no evidence of mechanical malfunctions.
A postaccident examination of the engine revealed no evidence of mechanical failures.
The engine was test run at various power settings after the accident.
No anomalies were noted during the post-accident engine test.
The National Transportation Safety Board determined the probable cause of the accident to be a total loss of engine power during a practice autorotation.
The reason for the loss of engine power could not be determined.

text:
# Aviation Investigation Final Report

## Location:
Pahrump, Nevada

## Date & Time: 
August 24, 2014, 06:50 Local

## Aircraft:
ROBINSON HELICOPTER COMPANY R44 II

## Defining Event:
Loss of engine power (total)

## Flight Conducted Under:
Part 91: General aviation - Personal

## Accident Number:
WPR14LA353

## Registration:
N4246Z

## Aircraft Damage:
Substantial

## Injuries:
1 Minor

## Analysis

The commercial pilot reported that, during a practice autorotation, a total loss of engine power occurred about 3,500 ft above ground level. The pilot made several unsuccessful attempts to restart the engine, and he subsequently performed an autorotation emergency landing. During the landing, the helicopter slid forward about 20 ft, the skids dug into the dry lakebed, and the helicopter then nosed over. Subsequently, the main rotor blades impacted the ground, and the helicopter came to rest on its side.

A postaccident examination of the airframe and engine revealed no evidence of mechanical malfunctions or failures that would have precluded normal operation. The engine was test run at various power settings with no anomalies noted.

## Probable Cause and Findings

The National Transportation Safety Board determines the probable cause(s) of this accident to be:

A total loss of engine power during a practice autorotation for reasons that could not be determined because postaccident examination of the airframe and engine did not reveal any anomalies that would have precluded normal operation.
